        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_2533_1_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Article in Salon yesterday highlights Cornell: https://www.salon.com/2021/12/19/depression-universities/</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_2533_2_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I know the guy.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_2533_2_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>He didn't mention it in the article, but he argued the admissions case all the way to the dean of arts and sciences, putting his own tenure at risk.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_2533_3_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Wow... that's exactly the kind of prejudice that the writer of the essay tried to draw attention to.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_2533_3_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>What if a high school applicant wrote an essay about dealing with diabetes?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_2533_3_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Or the challenges of their life in a wheelchair?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_2533_3_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>They shouldn't go to Cornell either?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_2533_4_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I know you mean well.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_2533_4_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But the issue here is that you're deciding for that Reggie kid what's best for him.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_2533_4_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Like telling a person with a wheelchair, "We won't let you into Cornell; honestly, you wouldn't like it; there are so many hills!"</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_2533_4_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>This is the very problem that disabled people face all the time -- it's not hatred or revulsion, it's condescension.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_2533_4_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>True respect means allowing people to decide for themselves what's best.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_2533_5_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Sorry, should have made clear: he was pre-tenure.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_2533_6_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Sarah Markowitz at MindWell is great.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_2533_6_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Thoughtful, smart, super professional.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_2533_6_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Also Denise Wittlin-Horvath, but she mostly focuses on meds I think.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_2533_7_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If this website is right, there's a bunch: https://scl.cornell.edu/residential-life/dining/eateries-menus just click "true" under "open now" and run the search</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_2533_8_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But think about it: what happens after you systematically weed out candidates who acknowledge their depression openly and show how they're fighting it?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_2533_8_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You're left with a campus where 100% of the depressed students (and there are MANY of them) are still hiding it, or in denial, and now they have no role models to help them cope -- ie, fellow students tackling the problem openly and courageously.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_2533_8_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Arguably, the administration creates a *more* dangerous environment for its depressed population by removing those who battle and triumph publicly.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
